fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Given relations R\colon A\mathbin {
rightarrow } B and S\colon B\mathbin {
rightarrow } C, we can define the relational composite S\circ R\colon A\mathbin {
rightarrow } C in a way that generalises composition of functions. In particular, we define S\circ R to be the following subset of A	imes C:

fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
\begin {aligned}
S\circ  R &\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } C\\
 S\circ  R &=
 {\mathopen {}\left \{
  {\mathopen {}\left (a,c\right )\mathclose {}}\in  A\times  C
  \mid 
  \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
  a\mathrel {R}b \land  b\mathrel {S} c
 \right \}\mathclose {}}
\end {aligned}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Recall the square root relation \mathsf {sq}\colon \mathbb {R}_{\geq 0}\mathbin {
rightarrow } \mathbb {R} from Example , and let \mathsf {neg} \colon \mathbb {R}\mathbin {
rightarrow }\mathbb {R} be the relation {\mathopen {}\left \{(x,y)\in \mathbb {R}^2\mid x = -yight \}\mathclose {}}. Then the relational composite \mathsf {neg}\circ \mathsf {sq}\colon \mathbb {R}_{\geq 0}\mathbin {
rightarrow }\mathbb {R} is equal to \mathsf {sq}.

To prove associativity, we fix relations R\colon A\mathbin {
rightarrow } B, S\colon B\mathbin {
rightarrow } C, and T\colon C\mathbin {
rightarrow } D to prove {\mathopen {}\left (T\circ Sight )\mathclose {}}\circ R = T\circ {\mathopen {}\left (S\circ Right )\mathclose {}}. To get started, we compute the intermediate composites:

fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
  \begin {aligned}
b\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (T\circ  S\right )\mathclose {}}}d &\Longleftrightarrow 
   \exists  c\in  C\mathpunct {.}
   b\mathrel {S}c\land  c\mathrel {T}d
   \\
   a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (S\circ  R\right )\mathclose {}}}c &\Longleftrightarrow 
   \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
   a\mathrel {R}b\land  b\mathrel {S}c
  \end {aligned}

\begin {aligned}
 a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left ({\mathopen {}\left (T\circ  S\right )\mathclose {}}\circ  R\right )\mathclose {}}} d
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b \land  b\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (T\circ  S\right )\mathclose {}}} d
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b \land  \exists  c\in  C\mathpunct {.}
 c\mathrel {S}c\land  c\mathrel {T}d
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 \exists  c\in  C\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b \land 
 b\mathrel {S}c\land  c\mathrel {T}d
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  c\in  C\mathpunct {.}
 {\mathopen {}\left (\exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b\land 
 b\mathrel {S}c\right )\mathclose {}}\land  c\mathrel {T}d
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  c\in  C\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (S\circ  R\right )\mathclose {}}}c\land  c\mathrel {T}d
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 a \mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (T\circ {\mathopen {}\left (S\circ  R\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}}d
\end {aligned}

\begin {aligned}
 a \mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (R\circ \mathsf {id}_{A}\right )\mathclose {}}} b
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  a'\in  A\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {\mathsf {id}_{A}}a' \land  a' \mathrel {R}b
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 \exists  a'\in  A\mathpunct {.}
 a = a' \land  a' \mathrel {R}b
 \\
 &\Longleftrightarrow 
 a \mathrel {R} b
\end {aligned}

\begin {aligned}
  {\mathopen {}\left ({\mathopen {}\left (N\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}\otimes  L\right )\mathclose {}}_{a,d} &=
  \bigoplus _{b\in {\mathopen {}\left  [l\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  {\mathopen {}\left (N\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}_{b,d}\odot  L_{a,b}
  \\
  &=
  \bigoplus _{b\in {\mathopen {}\left  [l\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  {\mathopen {}\left (
   \bigoplus _{c\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
   N_{c,d}\odot  M_{b,c}
  \right )\mathclose {}}
  \odot  L_{a,b}
  \\
  &=
  \bigoplus _{b\in {\mathopen {}\left  [l\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  \bigoplus _{c\in  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  N_{c,d}\odot  M_{b,c}\odot  L_{a,b}
  \\
  &=
  \bigoplus _{c\in  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  N_{c,d}\odot  \bigoplus _{b\in {\mathopen {}\left  [l\right  ]\mathclose {}}} M_{b,c}\odot  L_{a,b}
  \\
  &=
  \bigoplus _{c\in  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}}
  N_{c,d}\odot  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  L\right )\mathclose {}}_{a,c}
  \\
  &= {\mathopen {}\left (N\otimes {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  L\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}_{a,d}
\end {aligned}

\begin {aligned}
 {\mathopen {}\left (N\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}_{i,j} &= \bigoplus _{k\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}} N_{k,j}\odot  M_{i,k}
 \\
 &=
 \bigvee _{k\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}} N_{k,j}\land  M_{i,k}
 \\
 &=
 \exists  k\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\mathpunct {.}
 M_{i,k}\land  N_{k,j}
\end {aligned}

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:

We first unravel the first few M_k’s to get a better understanding.


  \begin {aligned}
   M_1 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_0\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n\oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M
   \\
   M_2 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_1\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  {\mathopen {}\left (I^n \oplus  M\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}} \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M \oplus  M^2
  \end {aligned}



By induction, we can extend the pattern above to a closed form for each M_k. In particular, we deduce that M_k = \bigoplus _{l\leq  k} M^l by recalling from Lemma  that the identity matrix is the neutral element for matrix multiplication. Therefore, we have M_n =\bigoplus _{k \leq  n}M^k.


Our goal is to show that M_n = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}} R^{\circ  *}; we have already seen in Lemma  and Lemma  that matrix addition corresponds to union of relations and matrix multiplication corresponds to relational composition.


By Observation  (Reflexive-transitive closure of finite endo-relations), we have R^{\circ *} = \bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}. Therefore:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ *} = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}



By Lemma  (matrix addition and union of relations), we have:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}
  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ  k}


 By Lemma  (matrix product is relational composition), we have:

